S.Figure 4

Associations between variance-based polygenic scores (vPGS) and phenotypic variabilty measured in unrelated indiviuals using squared z-scores, and in twin pairs via sibling-differences.

Models: Z2, squared z-scores regressed on vPGS using a linear model in a sample of unrelated individuals; MZ-diff, twin level phenotypic variability computed as the standard deviation (SD) for the twins phenotypic values, regressed on vPGS (identical for MZ twins; twin pair is the unit of analysis); DZ-diff, twin level phenotypic-SD values regressed on vPGS-SD values and the mean-vPGS value (vPGS vary in DZ twins; twin pair is the unit of analysis; estimated in same-sex pairs [ss] and opposite-sex pairs separately). vPGS were computed in TEDS participants, using GWA weights estimated from analyses of MoBa participants. LDpred2-auto was used to re-weight marginal SNP effects estimated from GWA, by integrating information from the SNP LD matrix, as well as the heritability and polygenicity of each trait. Communication: CCC, Childrens Communication Checklist (Ages 2 - 4); CDI, MacArthur Communicative Development Inventory (Age 9); Depression: SMFQ, Short Mood and Feelings Questionnaire; Hyperactivity & Inattention: CPRSRS, Conners Parent Rating Scale; Weight: residualised for the linear and quadratic effects of height
